         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">6/2/83. ¶  ¶ Only a few lines, dear Prof. Tate, to say, that I have critically and carefully examined a Cuscuta, obtained by Mr Chr Giles some years ago near Lady Charlotte's Waters, ¶  and find it a ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">83.02.06</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Ralph Tate</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Barr Smith Library, University of Adelaide, SA.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">6/2/83.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Only a few lines, dear Prof. Tate, to say, that I have critically and carefully examined a <name key="Cuscuta">Cuscuta</name>, obtained by Mr Chr Giles some years ago near Lady Charlotte's Waters,<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Charlotte waterhole, SA?</p>
               </note> and find it a 3- or 4-merous var. of C. australis. A similar form is known from S. Europe, not separate from the typical plant as a species; this was well shown by Engelmann.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See also M to G. Engelmann, 7 February 1883 (in this edition as 83-02-07a).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">You may be quite right as regards the Hypoxides. I took the small one for the true H.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Hypoxis</seg>
                     <seg style="">.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> glabella, because RBr. says of it in the prodromus expressly "scapo medio <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">bi</hi>
               </seg>bracteolato".<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>R. Brown (1810), p. 289.</p>
               </note> Hence Schlechtendal in 1846 took the larger plant of Dr Behrs collection from Tanunda as a new species, and named it H. vaginata, and in this way I disposed of both for years, til I thought it was best to unite the two, just as I joined H. pratensis to H hygrometrica.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Both unifications in B67.12.01, p.96.</p>
               </note> A crucial test for the validity would be the examination of the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">ripe seeds</hi>
               </seg>. We have a similar case with <name key="Arthropodium%20minus">Arthropodium minus</name> &amp; A. paniculatum.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>For discussion, see B70.1.01, pp. 66-7.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
